[{"id":38778,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>21</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>200</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>173</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The average power dissipated is,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>P</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>V</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>ϕ</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>10</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>60</mn><mo>°</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38841,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>94</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Z</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>100</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msup><mn>100</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>100</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#937;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Z</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mo>(</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>L</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mo>(</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>50</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>&#937;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>200</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mrow><mn>50</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>A</mtext></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>200</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mrow><mn>100</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>A</mtext></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><msub><mi>&#981;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>100</mn><mrow><mn>100</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>&#981;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><msub><mi>&#981;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>50</mn><mrow><mn>50</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>&#981;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/998ea0dc-cb5f-43a5-8398-0cd23b89328a-image.png\" style=\"width: 194px; height: 196px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msubsup><mi>I</mi><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>I</mi><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></msqrt><mo>;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>8</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>;</mo><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>10</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>This question is bonus as the correct answer was not available for students to mark as option in original paper by NTA.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38807,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5974ef8d-c2c7-4182-8b8c-16b222d64620-9894442.PNG\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 231px;\" /></p><p>We know that after long time an inductor offers&nbsp;zero resistance i.e., in steady state condition.</p><p>Here all three identical&nbsp;resistors are in parallel, so equivalent resistance is,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p>Now, current through the battery is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38899,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The energy stored in the capacitor is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>c</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. The energy stored in the inductor is given by.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>L</mi><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>. In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mi>C</mi></math>&nbsp;circuit there is no loss of energy in the form of heat so, using energy conservation,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi>c</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0.2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0.2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>5</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0.5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.17</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":38765,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} C & =2 \\mu f ; \\quad E=110 \\sqrt{2} \\sin (100 \\mathrm{t}) \\\\ \\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{C}} & =\\frac{1}{\\omega \\mathrm{c}}=\\frac{1}{100 \\times 2 \\times 10^{-6}} \\\\ = & \\frac{10000}{2}=5000 \\Omega \\\\ \\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{o}} & =\\frac{110 \\sqrt{2}}{5000} \\\\ \\mathrm{i}_{\\mathrm{rms}} & =\\frac{110 \\sqrt{2}}{5000 \\sqrt{2}} \\\\ & =\\frac{110}{5} \\mathrm{~mA} \\\\ & =22 \\mathrm{~mA}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38897,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5.17</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3.39</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2.26</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5.65</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>(Power factor), <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>&#8289;</mo><mtext>&#981;</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mi>Z</mi></mfrac></math></p><p>Where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Z</mi></math>&nbsp;are the resistance and impedance respectively.<br />(Energy dissipated)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mi>Z</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mtext>&#981;</mtext><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>t</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mi>Z</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mi>Z</mi></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>t</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>V</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;are the RMS voltage and time respectively.</p></blockquote><blockquote><p>We know that the Impedance of a&nbsp;LCR circuit is given by the formula,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mtext>&#969;</mtext><mi>L</mi><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mtext>&#969;</mtext><mi>C</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>60</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#960;</mtext><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#960;</mtext><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>50</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>120</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Where&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>&#969;</mtext><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>C</mi></math>&nbsp;are the angular frequency, inductance and capacitance in the circuit respectively.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>60</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mtext>&#960;</mtext><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1000</mn><mrow><mn>12</mn><mtext>&#960;</mtext></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4009</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>24</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>4009</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>60</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>= 517</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mtext>&#160;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5.17</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38753,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{rms}} \\mathrm{I}_{\\mathrm{rms}} \\cos \\phi \\\\ & \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{rms}} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{rms}}}{\\mathrm{z}} \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\mathrm{z}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{P}=\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{rms}}^2 \\times \\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\mathrm{z}^2} \\\\ & \\mathrm{z}=\\sqrt{\\mathrm{R}^2+\\left(\\mathrm{x}_{\\mathrm{L}}-\\mathrm{x}_{\\mathrm{C}}\\right)^2} \\\\ & \\mathrm{Z}=50 \\sqrt{2} \\Omega \\\\ & \\mathrm{P}=100 \\times \\frac{50}{2500 \\times 2}=1 \\mathrm{~W}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38840,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The given function of current is,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"{\"><mrow><msqrt><mn>42</mn></msqrt><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></mfrac><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>It means,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>42</mn><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></mfrac></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>20</mn><msqrt><mn>42</mn></msqrt><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mi>T</mi></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced close=\"&#62;\" open=\"&#60;\"><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>42</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>100</mn></math></p><p>RMS value of the current is,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>i</mi><mrow><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfenced open=\"&#60;\" close=\"&#62;\"><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfenced></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>121</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>11</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38927,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["C alone","R.L","L.C","L alone"],"answer":1,"solution":"$0 < $ phase difference for $R-L$ circuit $ < \\pi / 2$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":38876,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Given:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MHz</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Hz</mi></math></p><p>Since quality factor,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>L</mi></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>R</mi></mstyle></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>f</mi><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>L</mi></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>R</mi></mstyle></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>28</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Q</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>2000</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38755,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/QDP7pnPf9tyBeTpxm-ptLC7fU9u6rVc3rA8PrBxMuIY.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>$\\theta+\\theta=90^{\\circ} ; \\theta=45^{\\circ}$<br/>$\\tan \\theta=\\frac{\\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{C}}}{\\mathrm{R}}$<br/>$\\mathrm{X}_{\\mathrm{C}}=\\mathrm{R} \\Rightarrow \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{~W}_{\\mathrm{C}}}=\\mathrm{R}$<br/>$\\mathrm{W}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{C}}}=\\frac{1}{100 \\times 10^3 \\times 100 \\times 10^{-12}}$<br/>$=\\frac{10^{12}}{10^7}=10^5$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38788,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is correct but Statement II is false"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>When an a.c. voltage is applied in a series LCR circuit, the current is increased first, attains a maximum and then decreases.</p><p>The formula to calculate the power factor is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><msqrt><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><mfenced><mrow><msup><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>C</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></msqrt></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>At resonance,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>C</mi></msub></math>, Hence,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>cos</mi><msub><mi>&#981;</mi><mi>resonance</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>Thus, both the statements are true.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38751,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"From $V = 5\\sin(100t)$, angular frequency $\\omega = 100$ rad/s<br>At resonance in LCR circuit: $X_L = X_C$, so $\\omega L = \\frac{1}{\\omega C}$<br>Maximum current occurs at resonance: $I_{max} = \\frac{V_{rms}}{R}$<br>$50 \\times 10^{-3} = \\frac{5/\\sqrt{2}}{100}$ (verified at resonance)<br>From resonance condition: $100 \\times 2 = \\frac{1}{100 \\times C}$<br>$200 = \\frac{1}{100C}$<br>$C = \\frac{1}{20000} = 5 \\times 10^{-5}$ F = 50 μF","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38866,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfenced><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>90</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></msqrt><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>rms</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>+</mo><msubsup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></msqrt><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38745,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["$\\sqrt{\\dfrac{6}{7}}$","$\\sqrt{\\dfrac{3}{5}}$","$\\sqrt{\\dfrac{7}{8}}$","$\\sqrt{\\dfrac{3}{4}}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"The current in the RC circuit at frequency $\\omega$ is given by<br><br>$I = \\dfrac{V}{\\sqrt{R^2 + X_C^2}}$<br><br>where $X_C = \\dfrac{1}{\\omega C}$ is the capacitive reactance.<br><br>When the frequency is changed to $\\omega/4$, the new reactance becomes $X_C' = \\dfrac{1}{(\\omega/4)C} = 4X_C$.<br><br>The new current is given as $I/3$, so<br><br>$\\dfrac{I}{3} = \\dfrac{V}{\\sqrt{R^2 + (4X_C)^2}}$<br><br>Substituting the expression for $I$, we get<br><br>$\\dfrac{V}{3\\sqrt{R^2 + X_C^2}} = \\dfrac{V}{\\sqrt{R^2 + 16X_C^2}}$<br><br>Squaring both sides, we obtain<br><br>$\\dfrac{1}{9(R^2 + X_C^2)} = \\dfrac{1}{R^2 + 16X_C^2}$<br><br>$9R^2 + 9X_C^2 = R^2 + 16X_C^2$<br><br>$8R^2 = 7X_C^2$<br><br>$\\dfrac{R^2}{X_C^2} = \\dfrac{7}{8}$<br><br>$\\dfrac{R}{X_C} = \\sqrt{\\dfrac{7}{8}}$<br><br>Answer: $\\sqrt{\\dfrac{7}{8}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38860,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["Both, inductive reactance and current will<br />be halved.","Inductive reactance will be halved and<br />current will be doubled..","Inductive reactance will be doubled and<br />current will be halved.","Both, inducting reactance and current will be doubled"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>L</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38797,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#8486;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>28</mn><mo>&#8486;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#8486;</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>318</mn><mo>&#8486;</mo></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Comparing the given equation of AC voltage with standard expression, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>V</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>, we get&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>628</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p><p>Inductive reactance is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>L</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>L</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>628</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38858,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Alternating Current","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ms</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ms</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ms</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math> at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>i</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math> at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#969;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>&#960;</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi>f</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>400</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>ms</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null}]